******
[2]
Date: Tue 28 Apr 2015
Source: ABC (Australian Broadcasting Corporation), Radio Australia [edited]
http://www.radioaustralia.net.au/international/radio/program/pacific-beat/zika-virus-and-dengue-fever-infect-vanuatu/1440906


[This report contains a video clip that has the following transcription]

Vanuatu health officials have for the 1st time confirmed cases of the rare mosquito-borne Zika virus.

Zika is the "milder brother" of dengue fever, head of the World Health Organisation (WHO) in Vanuatu Jacob Kool said. The 2 illnesses share similar symptoms of fever, aching joints, and rash.

Although there were no recorded deaths from Zika [virus infections], health officials warned it can cause "very explosive outbreaks".

Like dengue fever, there is no cure for the Zika virus.

The WHO advises prevention through using mosquito nets, protective clothing and insect repellent, and removing breeding sites. Dr Kool told ABC's removing sites was "going to be very challenging" following the devastation caused by Cyclone Pam, which killed at least 11 people last month [March 2015]. "Breeding sites could be any cracked coconut, for example, and there's a lot of debris like that -- things that collect water where mosquitoes can breed," he said.

Zika was first discovered in 1947 in Rhesus Monkeys in Uganda's Zika forest. "Zika [virus] is a very strange story ... it had caused only about 20 known human cases until 2007, when there were suddenly 6000 cases on the island of Yap in the North Pacific," Dr Kool said.

The symptoms usually last 4-7 days. The mild symptoms and similarity to other illnesses may have been the reason for the low number of confirmed cases. "In hindsight, we think Zika [disease] has always been confused for dengue in many countries," Dr Kool said. "So Zika virus may have been around and always misdiagnosed for dengue."

In the aftermath of Cyclone Pam, medical teams reported several cases of pink eye to the WHO. "Pink eye, or red eye, is also a common symptom of Zika virus [infection]. So I wouldn't be surprised if those cases were [caused by] Zika virus as well," Dr Kool said.

